data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when called on an array. Expression trees **cannot represent** `Span`/`ReadOnlySpan` parameters, so this throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the call to bind to the `Enumerable` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version). The pattern is always the same: add `.AsEnumerable()`, cast to `IEnumerable<T>`, or call the `Enumerable.*` method explicitly.
